            "content": "# Raycaster Improvement Roadmap\n\nPending improvements, prioritized by impact. Completed items in [CHANGELOG.md](CHANGELOG.md).\n\n## P1: Architecture\n\n### 1. Float Tracer Redesign: DDA + Camera Plane\n**File**: `raycaster_float.c`\n\nThe float tracer uses intercept-based ray marching with separate horizontal/vertical passes and angle-index lookup tables. This is complex and tightly coupled to the fixed-point engine's precomputed data.\n\nRewrite as a clean DDA implementation with camera-plane FOV representation (inspired by cub3d). This is one task, not two -- DDA is the ray-marching algorithm, camera plane is the ray-generation model, and both belong together.\n\n**DDA ray march** (single loop, no trig inside):\n```c\nwhile (!hit) {\n    if (side_dist_x < side_dist_y) {\n        side_dist_x += delta_dist_x;\n        map_x += step_x;\n        side = 0;\n    } else {\n        side_dist_y += delta_dist_y;\n        map_y += step_y;\n        side = 1;\n    }\n    if (map[map_y][map_x] == WALL) hit = 1;\n}\n// Perpendicular distance eliminates fisheye without cos(deltaAngle) correction\n```\n\n**Camera plane ray generation** (no lookup tables):\n```c\ndouble camera_x = 2.0 * x / SCREEN_WIDTH - 1.0;\ndouble ray_dir_x = dir_x + plane_x * camera_x;\ndouble ray_dir_y = dir_y + plane_y * camera_x;\n// FOV = 2 * atan(plane_length) -- adjustable at runtime\n// Rotation via 2x2 matrix preserving orthogonality\n```\n\n**Why**: Makes `raycaster_float.c` a true standalone reference with zero dependency on precomputed tables. Simpler, faster, easier to verify against the fixed-point version.\n\n**Constraint**: Fixed-point tracer stays untouched (optimized for no-FPU targets).\n\n**Reference**: `externals/cub3d/src/raycasting.c`, `src/player_rotation.c`\n\n### 2. Runtime Map Configuration\n**File**: new `map_parser.c/h`\n\nDecouple map data from compiled code. Parse a text-based `.ray` format at startup:\n\n```\nT_N assets/textures/north.png\nT_S assets/textures/south.png\nT_W assets/textures/west.png\nT_E assets/textures/east.png\nF 40,40,40\nC 100,100,200\n\n1111111111\n1000000001\n100N000001\n1000000001\n1111111111\n```\n\n- Multi-pass validation: config lines, map grid, wall closure (flood-fill from player)\n- Player spawn from direction character (N/S/E/W)\n- Fall back to compiled-in `raycaster_data.c` when no file argument\n- Baremetal keeps compiled-in maps; SDL gains runtime loading\n\n**Reference**: `externals/cub3d/src/parsing/` (5 files, ~500 LOC)\n\n### 3. Direction-Based Wall Textures (NSWE)\n**File**: `renderer.c`\n\nAll four faces of a wall tile currently look identical. Select texture by hit face direction for visual orientation cues (standard since Wolf3D):\n\n```c\nif (side == 0)  // vertical wall hit\n    return (ray_dir_x > 0) ? &textures[EAST] : &textures[WEST];\nelse             // horizontal wall hit\n    return (ray_dir_y > 0) ? &textures[SOUTH] : &textures[NORTH];\n```\n\nCurrently both tracers only output `textureNo` as 0 (horizontal hit) or 1 (vertical hit) via the `Trace` callback. Neither computes NSWE direction. To implement this:\n1. Extend the `Trace` callback signature in `raycaster.h` to output ray direction signs (or encode NSWE directly into `textureNo` as 0-3).\n2. In `raycaster_fixed.c`, derive direction from `tileStepX`/`tileStepY` at the hit labels.\n3. In `raycaster_float.c`, derive direction from `sinA`/`cosA` sign at the hit comparison.\n4. In `renderer.c`, use the direction index to select from a 4-texture array in `RendererTraceFrame()`.\n\n**Reference**: `externals/cub3d/src/raycasting_3d.c:get_wall_texture()`\n\n## P2: Gameplay\n\n### 4. Doors\nExtend map format with door tile type. Reference: `doom-pico/inc/entities.h:25-27` (E_DOOR).\n\n### 5. Level Progression\nScene/level management via function pointer dispatch. E_EXIT tile type for transitions.\nReference: `doom-pico/src/game.c:1200-1251`\n\n### 6. Difficulty System\nParameterized constants affecting both offense and defense. Harder = enemies stronger AND player weaker.\nReference: `doom-pico/inc/constants.h:65-95`\n\n### 7. Sound Effects\nIntegrate SDL_mixer. Priority sounds: inhale, walk, hit_wall, medkit.\nReference: `doom-pico/inc/sound.h` (inverse frequency format, entire library < 1KB)\n\n### 8. Mouse Look\nMouse input for rotation (SDL target only).\n\n### 9. Simple Lighting Model\nSector-based brightness or Bayer dithering. Reference: `doom-pico/inc/display.h:59`\n\n### 10. Player Crouch/Stand\nPlayer pose enum affecting view height and collision. Reference: `externals/sciyen/game.h:9`\n\n## P3: Build & Quality\n\n### 11. Automatic Header Dependency Tracking\n**File**: `Makefile`\n\n```makefile\nDEPFLAGS = -MMD -MP\nCFLAGS += $(DEPFLAGS)\n-include $(SDL_OBJS:.o=.d)\n-include $(BAREMETAL_OBJS:.o=.d)\n```\n\n### 12. Deduplicate Core Source List\n**File**: `Makefile`\n\nSDL and baremetal targets compile overlapping source files (`game.c`, `raycaster.c`, `raycaster_fixed.c`, `raycaster_data.c`, `renderer.c`, `raycaster_tables.c`) with different compilers and flags. The source file names are listed redundantly in `SDL_OBJS` and `BAREMETAL_OBJS`. Factor out a `CORE_SRCS` variable and derive per-target object lists from it so adding a new shared source file only requires one edit.\n\nNote: objects must still be compiled separately (host CC for SDL, `arm-none-eabi-gcc` for baremetal).\n\n### 13. Const Correctness for Trace\n**File**: `raycaster.h`\n\nThe `Trace` function pointer takes `struct RayCaster *rayCaster` but never modifies the struct or its derived data during tracing. Change the signature to `const struct RayCaster *rayCaster`. `Start` (writes derived state) and `Destruct` (frees memory) cannot be const.\n\n### 14. Precalculator Truncation Warnings\n**File**: `tools/precalculator.c`\n\nWhen computed values exceed `uint16_t` range, `fminf()` silently clamps. Add stderr warnings during table generation so truncation is visible:\n\n```c\nfloat val = 256.0f * t;\nif (val > 65535.0f)\n    fprintf(stderr, \"Warning: tan[%d] clamped from %.2f\\n\", i, val);\ng_tan[i] = (uint16_t) fminf(val, 65535.0f);\n```\n\nThis is expected behavior for near-90-degree angles, but warnings help catch regressions if the table generation logic changes.\n\n## P4: Testing\n\n1. Edge case: player at exact grid boundaries (X.0, Y.0)\n2. Angle boundaries: 0, 90, 180, 270 degrees\n3. High velocity collision with maximum movement speed\n4. Memory: valgrind/ASan for leaks/overflows\n5. Fixed vs float visual parity validation\n\n## Reference Patterns (not actionable yet)\n\nThese doom-pico patterns are documented for when the corresponding gameplay features are implemented:\n\n- **Lazy Entity Spawning**: Spawn during raycasting when first visible, not at level load. `doom-pico/src/game.c:926-940`\n- **Projectile System**: Fireballs as entities, direction in health field, 90 discrete angles. `doom-pico/src/game.c:309-330`\n- **Packed Level Format**: 4-bit tile encoding, 64x57 map in 1824 bytes. `doom-pico/inc/level.h:12-16`\n- **Scene State Machine**: Function pointer dispatch, zero-allocation transitions. `doom-pico/src/game.c:24-61`\n- **Inverse Frequency Sound**: 1 byte/sample at 140 Hz, < 1KB total. `doom-pico/inc/sound.h`\n- **Dithering Gradients**: 2x4 Bayer patterns, 8 intensity levels. `doom-pico/inc/display.h:59`\n\n## Architectural Insight: 3D View Mirroring and Rotation\n\n### The Mirroring Problem\n\nThe raycaster's 3D view is inherently left-right mirrored due to the deltaAngle calculation in `tools/precalculator.c` and `raycaster_float.c`:\n\n```c\nfloat deltaAngle = atanf(((int16_t) i - SCREEN_WIDTH / 2.0f) /\n                         (SCREEN_WIDTH / 2.0f) * (float) M_PI / 4);\n```\n\n### Coordinate System\n\n```\nWorld coordinates (angle system 0-1023):\n    North (512, -Y)\n         |\nWest (768) --+-- East (256, +X)\n         |\n    South (0, +Y)\n\nplayerA increases: South(0) -> East(256) -> North(512) -> West(768)\n                   = Counter-clockwise in world coordinates\n```\n\n### The Rotation Paradox\n\nDue to mirroring, rotation creates opposite effects in 3D view vs world:\n\n| Action | World Effect | 3D View Effect |\n|--------|-------------|----------------|\n| playerA increases | CCW (South->East) | Scene scrolls LEFT (feels RIGHT) |\n| playerA decreases | CW (South->West) | Scene scrolls RIGHT (feels LEFT) |\n\nCurrent controls: Right arrow increases playerA, feels like turning right. Correct.\n\nMinimap shows true world direction (not mirrored). Trade-off accepted: minimap rotation appears opposite to 3D feel. This is world truth.\n\nNegating deltaAngle breaks textureNo and texture mapping. Would require rewriting the entire projection system.\n",
